  "iso639_3": "haw",
  "glottolog_code": "hawa1245",
  "notes": "Hawaiian (ʻŌlelo Hawaiʻi), Polynesian. The alphabet (pīʻāpā) has 13 letters: five vowels a e i o u, eight consonants h k l m n p w and the ʻokina ⟨ʻ⟩ = glottal stop /ʔ/, which is a full consonant. The kahakō (macron: ā ē ī ō ū) marks a long vowel. The orthography is essentially one-to-one phonemic. Allophony: /k/ varies [k]~[t] ([k] almost universally word-initially, [t] favoured before /i/); /w/ varies [w]~[v] ([v] usually after /i/ and /e/, [w] after /u/ and /o/); /l/ varies with [n] in some dialects. Diphthongs are written as vowel sequences and fall out of the single-vowel graphemes.",
